                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d364">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/642: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Siam</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mackenzie</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bangkok</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-12-09T17:00:00+07:00"
                            >December 9, 1929—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 9—10:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>31. Department’s circular of December 5, 4 p.m.<note n="97" xml:id="d364fn97">Not
                        printed.</note> The Siamese Minister for Foreign Affairs states that his
                    Government is in complete sympathy with the American action in calling the
                    attention of China and Russia to the obligations of the Pact of Paris, but he
                    will not make any further statement until the King, who is at the winter palace
                    in the country now, has instructed him. A public statement is, therefore, not
                    decided upon. The local press is noncommittal.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mackenzie</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
